Reference-contexts: Artificial bidding agents can represent the preferences of consumers, consumers can be physically distributed, bidding is electronic, and auction clearing is fully automatic. Auctions are just a first step towards more sophisticated negotiation for electronic commerce <ref> (Beam et. al. 1996) </ref>. The design of mechanisms and bidding agents for on-line auctions should be informed by the costs placed on human participants, the possibilities for effective agent mediation, and also by the trust properties of the auction. <p> In a traditional off-line auction this includes the cost of getting all the bidders together in the same place on the same day. The distinction between single-shot and repeated mechanisms in agent-mediated auctions is less important because communication costs are much lower than in off-line auctions <ref> (Beam et al. 1996) </ref>.
Reference: <author> Guttman, R., Maes, P.: </author> <title> Agent-mediated Integrative Negotiation for Retail Electronic Commerce. Workshop on Agent Mediated Electronic Trading (AMET-98), </title> <year> 1998. </year>
Reference-contexts: Agent-mediated negotiation absorbs many of the costs, and on-line retail allows bidding-agents to readily negotiate with many sellers. First-generation shopping agents compare the price of goods over fixed-price retail sites. A natural extension is to allow agents to dynamically negotiate terms of agreement <ref> (Guttman and Maes 1998) </ref>. The design of market-aware computational agents presents a key challenge for agent technologies and artificial intelligence in general (Wellman and Wurman 1997). Market mechanisms can be designed to enable simple and provably optimal agent strategies in simple domains (Varian 1995). <p> Auctions are simply well-defined sets of rules for negotiation. Traditional auctions allow negotiation over price alone, which is clearly undesirable in a marketplace with simultaneous auctions over dissimilar goods, for example goods with different warranties or service policies <ref> (Guttman and Maes 1998) </ref>. Auction protocols can however be extended to permit wider negotiation, still within a framework that allows for the possibility of insincere agents and strategic behavior.
