Reference-contexts: Traditional auction theory emphasizes the allocation efficiency and expected revenue properties of different auction types, given different assumptions about how a bidder's value of a good is formed <ref> (McAfee and McMillan 1987) </ref>. <p> The English auction maximizes revenue for sellers because bids reveal information <ref> (McAfee and McMillan 1987) </ref>, and the knowledge that one bidder values the item highly may increase the valuations of the other bidders. A sealed-bid auction does not allow dynamic information sharing between bidding agents.
